WEBVTT

00:00:00.020 --> 00:00:03.620
All right, let's do this.

00:00:03.620 --> 00:00:04.520
Hi, everyone.

00:00:04.520 --> 00:00:06.840
Thanks for being here.

00:00:06.840 --> 00:00:07.560
Who's here?

00:00:07.560 --> 00:00:08.200
My friends?

00:00:08.230 --> 00:00:10.230
My colleagues?

00:00:10.230 --> 00:00:11.130
Great.

00:00:11.130 --> 00:00:11.890
Okay.

00:00:11.890 --> 00:00:13.080
I am Tessa.

00:00:13.080 --> 00:00:17.200
I am the CEO and co-founder of Germ Network.

00:00:17.520 --> 00:00:20.710
I'm here with my founding engineer, Anna, who I

00:00:20.710 --> 00:00:22.480
hope many of you will get to meet.

00:00:22.530 --> 00:00:25.140
If you have technical questions, you should really ask her and

00:00:25.140 --> 00:00:25.510
not me.

00:00:25.670 --> 00:00:29.820
We build an end-to-end encrypted messenger that lets

00:00:29.930 --> 00:00:33.560
you log in with social handles instead of a phone number.

00:00:33.580 --> 00:00:38.560
Germ supports multiple identities, and at proto is our first and

00:00:38.560 --> 00:00:40.430
maybe most important stop.

00:00:40.460 --> 00:00:48.500
Germ now launches from your blue sky, black

00:00:48.500 --> 00:00:53.270
sky, and other at proto profiles.

00:00:53.270 --> 00:00:58.310
So thousands of you have used it since we integrate it into

00:00:58.310 --> 00:00:59.840
your blue sky profiles.

00:00:59.840 --> 00:01:02.820
Thank you for sharing your feedback in the last few weeks,

00:01:02.820 --> 00:01:07.230
and to the app proto developers who are already implementing the germ

00:01:07.230 --> 00:01:10.080
button in your app views for your users.

00:01:10.410 --> 00:01:10.910
Thank you.

00:01:11.120 --> 00:01:12.950
We have a lot of work to do, but we are

00:01:12.950 --> 00:01:18.310
ready to be your secure messaging app for the atmosphere and beyond

00:01:18.310 --> 00:01:18.430
.

00:01:18.430 --> 00:01:21.660
Come find Anna and I at 9:00 AM tomorrow morning

00:01:21.660 --> 00:01:24.190
in the lounge, the like round lounge upstairs.

00:01:24.240 --> 00:01:26.080
We're going to play with germ, and we would love

00:01:26.120 --> 00:01:27.300
to hear your feedback.

00:01:27.430 --> 00:01:29.680
And I have one green germ hat to give away.

00:01:29.680 --> 00:01:34.260
So my co-founder and CTO, Mark, is

00:01:34.260 --> 00:01:35.740
watching from home in LA.

00:01:35.790 --> 00:01:37.430
Hey, Mark, we miss you.

00:01:38.380 --> 00:01:41.030
Mark and I met on Twitter.

00:01:41.100 --> 00:01:45.180
I was a social media scholar with a theory about the centr

00:01:45.180 --> 00:01:47.660
ality of messaging to social.

00:01:47.680 --> 00:01:51.260
And Mark was the ex-Apple iMessage

00:01:51.260 --> 00:01:55.800
and FaceTime privacy engineer who left to replace the phone number

00:01:55.800 --> 00:01:56.140
.

00:01:56.140 --> 00:01:59.440
It's hard to believe that a year ago, he and

00:01:59.440 --> 00:02:03.250
I came to Seattle for AtConf as perfect strangers to everyone

00:02:03.250 --> 00:02:07.100
here because we had just started integrating AppProto into our

00:02:07.100 --> 00:02:09.640
messaging app.

00:02:09.790 --> 00:02:14.060
That weekend, we had some exciting conversations about privacy and private

00:02:14.060 --> 00:02:17.580
data that a year later are bearing so much fruit.

00:02:17.710 --> 00:02:20.220
And even at Germ, as we're focused on building end

00:02:20.220 --> 00:02:23.010
-to-end encrypted channels for your AppProto handles

00:02:23.010 --> 00:02:27.260
, we're also really interested in private data, both as

00:02:27.360 --> 00:02:30.760
developers who might use it and also as users and as citizens

00:02:30.980 --> 00:02:34.700
of this ecosystem who care about the future of social networking.

00:02:34.720 --> 00:02:37.980
But today, I don't want to talk about privacy.

00:02:37.980 --> 00:02:39.900
I want to talk about consent.

00:02:43.420 --> 00:02:46.830
In this community, we talk a lot about openness, self

00:02:46.890 --> 00:02:50.060
-determination, privacy, and choice.

00:02:50.070 --> 00:02:54.000
These are North Star values that orient us around what we're

00:02:54.020 --> 00:02:54.700
building.

00:02:54.710 --> 00:03:00.380
But these words fundamentally each describe a position of the self.

00:03:00.380 --> 00:03:03.000
I am open or private.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:04.780
I have choices.

00:03:04.780 --> 00:03:07.980
But as soon as I tell you what to do, these

00:03:07.980 --> 00:03:09.000
terms collapse.

00:03:11.040 --> 00:03:14.610
Consent is the missing principle here because consent is a principle

00:03:14.610 --> 00:03:15.690
of relationality.

00:03:15.830 --> 00:03:20.300
Relationality is hard because it's dynamic.

00:03:20.300 --> 00:03:23.580
It demands continual negotiation.

00:03:23.590 --> 00:03:28.220
But it's also strong because it produces consensus.

00:03:28.330 --> 00:03:33.810
Consent is scalable because it extends from a two-person

00:03:33.940 --> 00:03:38.530
relationship to the relationship of people to their government and to their

00:03:38.530 --> 00:03:39.970
social rules and norms.

00:03:40.140 --> 00:03:46.870
Caring about consent translates to movement coherence and political durability

00:03:46.870 --> 00:03:47.020
.

00:03:47.130 --> 00:03:51.660
Building consensual systems is building systems to last.

00:03:51.660 --> 00:03:53.510
And I think that's what we're all trying to do

00:03:53.630 --> 00:03:53.740
here.

00:03:53.760 --> 00:03:58.140
It's also simply the price of healthy relating.

00:03:58.710 --> 00:04:02.700
And I believe that every single person at this conference builds technology

00:04:02.700 --> 00:04:06.470
to serve human flourishing, choice, and community well-

00:04:06.470 --> 00:04:06.780
being.

00:04:06.780 --> 00:04:09.440
We're all building the future that we want to live in

00:04:09.570 --> 00:04:09.720
.

00:04:09.760 --> 00:04:13.450
So today, I want to offer us that consent is and

00:04:13.700 --> 00:04:17.340
should be one of the core guiding values that we unite around

00:04:17.340 --> 00:04:18.370
to reach our goals.

00:04:20.460 --> 00:04:22.460
I want to offer consent as a resource.

00:04:22.470 --> 00:04:26.610
Consent is a concept that you can return to when you

00:04:26.610 --> 00:04:31.500
're setting goals, designing products, and engaging with users.

00:04:31.510 --> 00:04:33.820
Also known as other people.

00:04:37.120 --> 00:04:39.250
This talk is not graphic, but I do just want to

00:04:39.250 --> 00:04:42.990
give a trigger warning that I will mention interpersonal and sexual violence

00:04:42.990 --> 00:04:43.170
.

00:04:43.180 --> 00:04:44.780
So please take care of yourself.

00:04:44.790 --> 00:04:48.880
So the internet that most of the world lives in today is

00:04:48.910 --> 00:04:52.700
characterized by surveillance and control.

00:04:52.720 --> 00:04:55.330
That's why we're building the alternative, right?

00:04:57.040 --> 00:05:00.670
Modern social media is a gilded cage where people trade

00:05:00.980 --> 00:05:06.060
their information, relationships, attention, and ultimately freedom of thought

00:05:06.060 --> 00:05:10.410
for a steady drip of content that promises connection like a carrot

00:05:10.410 --> 00:05:12.300
that you can never quite reach.

00:05:12.320 --> 00:05:17.870
Over 6 billion people are on the internet and 4 billion human

00:05:18.020 --> 00:05:22.610
beings are using meta products every single month.

00:05:23.760 --> 00:05:26.040
These are the people that we're trying to recruit to the

00:05:26.040 --> 00:05:26.680
atmosphere.

00:05:26.710 --> 00:05:31.260
We've lived in meta social internet for 20 years, and

00:05:31.260 --> 00:05:33.890
I thought it would be fun to remind us how it started

00:05:34.060 --> 00:05:34.220
.

00:05:34.220 --> 00:05:38.280
A Facebook for the younger folks here used to be a kind

00:05:38.280 --> 00:05:42.940
of yearbook that colleges would distribute at the beginning of the

00:05:42.940 --> 00:05:45.420
school year to help undergrads make friends.

00:05:45.440 --> 00:05:48.050
Because it's always natural for us to look for each other

00:05:48.210 --> 00:05:48.360
.

00:05:48.380 --> 00:05:52.100
So in the early 2000s, Harvard made these digital.

00:05:52.630 --> 00:05:56.710
There are 12 residential houses on campus, like big dorm complexes

00:05:56.770 --> 00:05:59.900
, and they each had their own private online Facebook.

00:05:59.900 --> 00:06:02.970
So Mark Zuckerberg, when he was an undergrad, hacked

00:06:03.010 --> 00:06:04.000
into each one.

00:06:04.020 --> 00:06:08.950
He downloaded every single image of an undergraduate woman at Harvard and

00:06:08.950 --> 00:06:11.790
fed them into a hot or not style website that he then

00:06:11.910 --> 00:06:12.840
distributed.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:17.140
Luckily for him, the president of the school at the time

00:06:17.140 --> 00:06:17.900
was this guy.

00:06:19.660 --> 00:06:24.330
Zuck received zero discipline for hacking school IT systems and sexually

00:06:24.330 --> 00:06:28.940
harassing every single undergraduate woman on campus, which probably included

00:06:28.940 --> 00:06:29.320
minors.

00:06:29.430 --> 00:06:34.080
He was able to build and launch Facebook with campus resources,

00:06:34.110 --> 00:06:37.190
got to drop out of his own free will, and then

00:06:37.310 --> 00:06:39.600
this guy wired him $500,000.

00:06:41.750 --> 00:06:45.380
In the 20 years since, he's built so many beautiful

00:06:45.700 --> 00:06:49.350
businesses that all of us around the world get to enjoy today

00:06:49.420 --> 00:06:49.740
.

00:06:53.860 --> 00:07:01.350
Today, the way 70 to 80% of Americans feel about

00:07:01.420 --> 00:07:08.700
how companies and the government handle our data is distrust,

00:07:08.700 --> 00:07:10.860
lack of control, and confusion.

00:07:10.880 --> 00:07:17.130
This is a picture of authoritarianism that predates our current

00:07:17.130 --> 00:07:19.180
administration.

00:07:19.190 --> 00:07:22.120
Social media has connected the world, but it has also traumat

00:07:22.220 --> 00:07:22.880
ized the world.

00:07:23.110 --> 00:07:25.940
We want to talk to anyone, we don't want to

00:07:25.950 --> 00:07:27.420
talk to everyone.

00:07:29.500 --> 00:07:32.470
It's time for us to build new products with the love

00:07:32.540 --> 00:07:35.570
and tenderness that make it safe and easy for people to

00:07:35.680 --> 00:07:38.780
trust us and depend on us for the rest of their lives

00:07:38.860 --> 00:07:39.040
.

00:07:39.320 --> 00:07:43.790
Luckily for us, consent is a renewable resource that we produce

00:07:43.790 --> 00:07:44.700
ourselves.

00:07:47.920 --> 00:07:52.560
Defined simply, consent is agreement to what someone else proposed

00:07:52.560 --> 00:07:55.090
or is doing that involves you.

00:07:55.110 --> 00:07:58.800
In fact, it's a concept with a thousand-year

00:07:59.060 --> 00:08:04.540
history that bridges contract law, political theory, sexual health,

00:08:04.540 --> 00:08:06.320
human rights, and data policy.

00:08:06.470 --> 00:08:10.460
So whether you're talking about consenting to a contract,

00:08:10.460 --> 00:08:14.180
to being governed, to sex, to data collection, it

00:08:14.180 --> 00:08:15.260
's all the same idea.

00:08:15.260 --> 00:08:17.500
So it's obviously a hugely important concept.

00:08:17.510 --> 00:08:22.230
In the 1990s, anti-rape activists on college

00:08:22.800 --> 00:08:27.460
campuses pushed the theory of consent into affirmative consent, which from

00:08:27.460 --> 00:08:28.720
there moved into law.

00:08:28.870 --> 00:08:32.580
Affirmative consent has five parameters.

00:08:32.720 --> 00:08:37.100
It's voluntary, so of course, it's freely given

00:08:37.100 --> 00:08:41.080
, it's informed, people need to understand what they're

00:08:41.420 --> 00:08:41.980
consenting to.

00:08:44.540 --> 00:08:47.050
It's revertible, it's reversible, which means

00:08:47.150 --> 00:08:49.900
it's continually given and you can withdraw it.

00:08:49.910 --> 00:08:53.440
It's specific, so consent is to a specific ask,

00:08:53.440 --> 00:08:56.380
it's not a blanket permissiveness.

00:08:56.400 --> 00:08:58.640
And finally, it's unburdensome, it

00:08:58.640 --> 00:09:02.300
's easy to give, otherwise it's not really accessible.

00:09:05.350 --> 00:09:08.750
But in the context of software, consent has remained really shallow

00:09:08.810 --> 00:09:09.000
.

00:09:09.030 --> 00:09:13.680
Permission screens, cloud, are access to information and services

00:09:13.680 --> 00:09:16.260
, and we're coerced into consenting.

00:09:16.280 --> 00:09:18.140
That's not, that's not the deal.

00:09:18.160 --> 00:09:25.700
In 2021, human-computer interaction scholar Jane Im challenged

00:09:25.700 --> 00:09:28.730
us to apply the most current theories of consent to how we

00:09:29.090 --> 00:09:30.340
design social media features.

00:09:31.840 --> 00:09:38.460
She has this extraordinary table where she categorizes or generates social

00:09:38.460 --> 00:09:42.300
media features across the five categories of affirmative consent.

00:09:42.310 --> 00:09:46.460
This table is an actual laundry list of the best features that

00:09:46.460 --> 00:09:50.220
we've been begging platforms for for 20 years.

00:09:50.220 --> 00:09:53.160
It includes a lot of the stuff that we're working on

00:09:53.160 --> 00:09:58.420
here in the atmosphere, like algorithmic choice and account labels

00:09:58.420 --> 00:10:01.900
, the ability to disconnect posts from their engagement.

00:10:03.020 --> 00:10:06.660
It is also extremely generative, with new ideas for automation

00:10:06.980 --> 00:10:09.580
and organization and personalization.

00:10:09.590 --> 00:10:13.280
The first line of this chart is DMs.

00:10:13.500 --> 00:10:16.670
It has some really awesome feature ideas that we've talked about

00:10:16.670 --> 00:10:19.570
at Germ when we think towards group chats, automations,

00:10:19.680 --> 00:10:21.100
and productivity features.

00:10:21.120 --> 00:10:25.540
And Germ's agentive multi-identity technology is going

00:10:25.540 --> 00:10:27.100
to make some of this really easy.

00:10:27.440 --> 00:10:30.360
Like automations based on who you're talking to and who

00:10:30.460 --> 00:10:31.500
they know you as.

00:10:31.510 --> 00:10:37.380
But consent in messaging starts earlier than that, because a DM

00:10:37.380 --> 00:10:41.420
is the minimum viable product of a digital relationship.

00:10:41.440 --> 00:10:45.810
The same way a two-person connection is the smallest unit

00:10:45.810 --> 00:10:47.260
of a community.

00:10:49.020 --> 00:10:50.270
So let's talk about Germ.

00:10:50.320 --> 00:10:53.940
We've heard a lot about App Proto ethos.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:56.460
We also have a Germ ethos.

00:10:56.460 --> 00:11:00.180
I resonated so strongly last year to Paul Frazee's

00:11:00.420 --> 00:11:03.180
talk on Blue Sky's theory of change.

00:11:03.190 --> 00:11:06.470
Germ is similar to Blue Sky in that we are also a

00:11:06.470 --> 00:11:09.660
product built on top of an open protocol.

00:11:09.680 --> 00:11:14.160
Our protocol will always be interoperable, open source,

00:11:14.160 --> 00:11:15.100
and free.

00:11:15.110 --> 00:11:18.700
And we'll build our business through our product or products.

00:11:19.660 --> 00:11:22.290
We also believe that the way to grow how many people we

00:11:22.290 --> 00:11:25.420
serve is to compete as a consumer startup.

00:11:25.420 --> 00:11:29.060
So we're a public benefit corporation that's using growth capital

00:11:29.060 --> 00:11:30.530
to build our business.

00:11:30.550 --> 00:11:35.320
But if the AT protocol is locked open, Germ's protocol

00:11:36.240 --> 00:11:38.700
is locked consensual.

00:11:38.720 --> 00:11:45.500
Germ starts from the technological equivalent of a human rights posture.

00:11:46.550 --> 00:11:48.920
That you, each of you, are a self-so

00:11:48.920 --> 00:11:53.080
vereign individual with inalienable rights to your person

00:11:53.080 --> 00:11:56.130
hood, which in the digital realm is expressed as data.

00:11:57.830 --> 00:12:02.460
From that foundation, you have the power to identify yourself and

00:12:02.460 --> 00:12:05.580
to form relationships expressed as sharing data.

00:12:05.600 --> 00:12:11.060
Each relationship you form is unique, is double opt-in

00:12:11.280 --> 00:12:12.510
, and a single opt-out.

00:12:13.360 --> 00:12:21.700
Our protocol is an authentication layer on top of the messaging

00:12:22.060 --> 00:12:26.860
layer security protocol for end-to-end encrypted messaging.

00:12:26.870 --> 00:12:31.270
So the relationships that you opt into on Germ exist in a

00:12:31.270 --> 00:12:35.270
completely private session between you and the person you're talking to

00:12:35.460 --> 00:12:35.490
.

00:12:36.640 --> 00:12:40.010
You choose to talk to someone, also known as sharing data

00:12:40.010 --> 00:12:43.270
in real time with them, and you're only sharing it

00:12:43.270 --> 00:12:44.220
with them.

00:12:44.230 --> 00:12:47.870
So this is cryptography in the service of how we really

00:12:48.180 --> 00:12:51.020
form and dissolve human relationships.

00:12:53.190 --> 00:12:56.120
End-to-end encrypted messaging started off centralized.

00:12:56.150 --> 00:12:59.860
Both parties have to be on the same service, and you

00:13:00.100 --> 00:13:04.330
send encrypted messages addressed to and from the identities of the two

00:13:04.330 --> 00:13:04.940
parties.

00:13:04.950 --> 00:13:08.080
Historically, those have been phone numbers, but in recent

00:13:08.080 --> 00:13:10.780
years, those have been things like crypto wallets.

00:13:10.800 --> 00:13:17.920
Germ decentralizes authentication with our novel protocol, which is inspired

00:13:17.920 --> 00:13:18.970
by Double Ratchet.

00:13:20.470 --> 00:13:22.630
Double Ratchet is the gold standard of end-to-

00:13:22.630 --> 00:13:27.380
end encrypted messaging, and it updates encryption keys with each message

00:13:27.420 --> 00:13:27.900
sent.

00:13:28.040 --> 00:13:34.420
Similarly, our protocol updates identity and transport when you message people

00:13:34.430 --> 00:13:34.780
.

00:13:34.800 --> 00:13:40.530
This gives us a powerful primitive that breaks free of fixed identities

00:13:40.530 --> 00:13:42.380
and centralized services.

00:13:42.490 --> 00:13:49.790
Our protocol frees end-to-end encrypted communication from

00:13:49.790 --> 00:13:50.380
phone numbers.

00:13:51.020 --> 00:13:54.380
So that you can communicate as multiple agentive identities.

00:13:54.380 --> 00:13:57.660
So we're building secure messaging beyond phone numbers.

00:13:57.680 --> 00:14:01.070
There's a theory of relationship here.

00:14:01.110 --> 00:14:05.280
If a message is the MVP of a digital relationship, that

00:14:05.280 --> 00:14:09.460
means we're only connected if we're communicating.

00:14:10.870 --> 00:14:13.260
There aren't inactive follows on Germ.

00:14:13.280 --> 00:14:16.960
The connection starts only when I send you a message.

00:14:17.200 --> 00:14:22.340
Identification is part of communication, not separate from it.

00:14:22.350 --> 00:14:25.720
When I talk to you, I identify myself to you.

00:14:25.720 --> 00:14:28.140
It's the first thing that I share and not before.

00:14:28.150 --> 00:14:32.210
Like Krishnamurti said, I cannot exist in

00:14:32.210 --> 00:14:33.020
myself.

00:14:33.020 --> 00:14:35.020
I only exist in relationship.

00:14:35.020 --> 00:14:38.610
On Germ, you don't exist without your relationships.

00:14:38.630 --> 00:14:43.790
The coercive internet is based on a very dark view of

00:14:44.320 --> 00:14:45.200
humanity.

00:14:45.210 --> 00:14:49.260
That we can only be tricked into engaging with each other.

00:14:50.630 --> 00:14:52.800
The history of the world would beg to differ.

00:14:52.810 --> 00:14:56.440
At Germ, we're idealists, but we're also

00:14:56.760 --> 00:14:57.470
realists.

00:14:57.710 --> 00:15:02.180
So many of us lately at this conference and online beforehand have

00:15:02.180 --> 00:15:05.760
been talking about how we need to make our products effortless

00:15:05.760 --> 00:15:06.550
and inviting.

00:15:07.160 --> 00:15:09.760
Like I used to tell my students, you can't follow

00:15:09.980 --> 00:15:13.060
your paper around explaining what you meant to say.

00:15:13.070 --> 00:15:18.140
As Tony Cade Bambara says, the role of

00:15:18.140 --> 00:15:21.060
the artist is to make revolution irresistible.

00:15:21.070 --> 00:15:25.720
At Germ, our goal is to make exercising your autonomy feel

00:15:25.720 --> 00:15:28.660
effortless and fun, even viral.

00:15:28.670 --> 00:15:33.300
And so the core UX challenge of our app is making it

00:15:33.300 --> 00:15:36.420
easy and intuitive to talk to your friends with your handle.

00:15:37.080 --> 00:15:40.360
While placing authentic moments of friction in the right places.

00:15:40.360 --> 00:15:44.460
We tried not to reinvent the wheel where messaging works well,

00:15:44.510 --> 00:15:49.210
but innovate significantly in the context layer with our creation of cards

00:15:49.260 --> 00:15:49.500
.

00:15:49.500 --> 00:15:56.960
Cards are how we represent your cryptographic identities in Germ

00:15:56.960 --> 00:15:57.420
.

00:15:57.430 --> 00:16:01.120
You can use cards without app proto.

00:16:01.280 --> 00:16:03.880
You just build one and share a link or a QR code

00:16:04.050 --> 00:16:05.820
with someone else to chat.

00:16:06.990 --> 00:16:11.200
Under the hood, that is decentralized authentication, but most users

00:16:11.200 --> 00:16:12.320
don't care.

00:16:12.340 --> 00:16:16.340
You can build multiple cards and each version of every card you

00:16:16.340 --> 00:16:20.680
share is operating a separate cryptographic mailbox, all presented to

00:16:20.680 --> 00:16:22.550
you in one unified inbox.

00:16:24.280 --> 00:16:27.840
As we integrated app proto, we navigated new dimensions of

00:16:27.840 --> 00:16:30.620
how our users grant and withdraw consent.

00:16:30.630 --> 00:16:34.260
Germ's burner cards are totally local, but your app proto

00:16:34.580 --> 00:16:37.420
card is connected to this busy outside world.

00:16:37.440 --> 00:16:41.120
You pull your profile data in from app proto and you can

00:16:41.380 --> 00:16:43.740
push things back out like blocks.

00:16:43.740 --> 00:16:44.290
We already present your products.

00:16:44.340 --> 00:16:48.050
We already present your app proto card differently from your local cards

00:16:48.300 --> 00:16:50.960
, but I expect that as our app matures, our

00:16:50.960 --> 00:16:54.950
design system will highlight where your cards and relationships came from.

00:16:57.860 --> 00:17:01.250
All relationships on Germ are two-way, but app proto

00:17:01.260 --> 00:17:04.760
doesn't have friends, it has one-way followers.

00:17:04.810 --> 00:17:08.430
If Germ is invite-only messaging, when you link your

00:17:08.430 --> 00:17:12.300
app proto handle, you're opening up a wider invitation of

00:17:12.300 --> 00:17:13.210
who can talk to you.

00:17:13.420 --> 00:17:15.700
But even there, we don't assume.

00:17:16.180 --> 00:17:19.210
We use the logics of consent to reason about how to

00:17:19.220 --> 00:17:21.880
bring app proto connections into Germ.

00:17:21.890 --> 00:17:26.070
If you follow someone on app proto, you opted into connecting

00:17:26.070 --> 00:17:27.030
with them.

00:17:27.040 --> 00:17:29.920
So they can double opt-in back to you by messaging

00:17:29.920 --> 00:17:30.760
you on Germ.

00:17:30.850 --> 00:17:34.130
And all across the atmosphere, we're seeing the Germ button

00:17:34.130 --> 00:17:36.380
showing up on your friend's profile.

00:17:36.400 --> 00:17:38.830
Just click it and start chatting with them in an end-

00:17:38.830 --> 00:17:40.360
to-end encrypted channel.

00:17:40.370 --> 00:17:43.560
And we hear you asking for open DMs.

00:17:43.660 --> 00:17:45.880
You're ready to consent to that.

00:17:45.880 --> 00:17:47.070
And that's a future feature.

00:17:47.100 --> 00:17:50.640
Because consent is informed, we want to make sure that our

00:17:50.640 --> 00:17:53.920
users always know what they're sharing with who.

00:17:53.940 --> 00:17:57.330
Because it's specific, we want them to have granular control

00:17:57.340 --> 00:17:59.420
over how they can be contacted.

00:17:59.420 --> 00:18:02.690
So you decide whether you want the people that you follow on

00:18:02.690 --> 00:18:05.230
app proto to be able to message you at all, or

00:18:05.230 --> 00:18:08.050
whether you want to reserve the right to send the first message

00:18:08.050 --> 00:18:10.960
, and whether a button to Germ DM should display in app

00:18:11.070 --> 00:18:11.540
views.

00:18:12.320 --> 00:18:13.840
Because it's unburdensome.

00:18:13.840 --> 00:18:16.180
If you chat with someone, if you want to chat with

00:18:16.180 --> 00:18:19.700
someone, if you can chat with someone, excuse me,

00:18:19.710 --> 00:18:22.140
you see a button on their profile, and you simply click

00:18:22.140 --> 00:18:23.280
it to start chatting.

00:18:23.290 --> 00:18:26.850
And this is the fun part about consent.

00:18:26.880 --> 00:18:30.500
People get mad when they don't have access to your permission

00:18:30.820 --> 00:18:32.420
to hang out with them.

00:18:32.770 --> 00:18:35.390
But to the people that you consent to be in relationship with

00:18:35.600 --> 00:18:37.260
, it's the best party in the world.

00:18:37.270 --> 00:18:41.920
Germ relationships are separate from app proto relationships.

00:18:41.940 --> 00:18:45.590
So once you start messaging on Germ via your app proto cards

00:18:45.900 --> 00:18:48.340
, you can, for example, unfollow each other out

00:18:48.340 --> 00:18:50.400
there, and you'll still be connected in Germ.

00:18:50.410 --> 00:18:53.630
You can even disconnect your blue sky account, or your black

00:18:53.660 --> 00:18:56.390
sky account, and you still can keep talking on Germ.

00:18:56.540 --> 00:19:02.010
Right now, you add Germ friends one at a time from

00:19:02.140 --> 00:19:03.300
another app.

00:19:03.320 --> 00:19:06.950
But we're working to show your app proto social graph inside

00:19:07.260 --> 00:19:09.810
of Germ, so that you can have a more complete and

00:19:09.920 --> 00:19:11.510
easy messaging experience.

00:19:12.300 --> 00:19:15.710
In designing this new feature, we wanted to help people understand

00:19:15.720 --> 00:19:19.150
that your app proto connections aren't your Germ connections, until

00:19:19.230 --> 00:19:20.490
you send them a message.

00:19:20.510 --> 00:19:22.960
You can also dismiss seeing people in the app, like in

00:19:22.960 --> 00:19:24.820
other suggested friends features.

00:19:24.830 --> 00:19:28.230
So Germ is not just a messenger for app proto the way

00:19:28.230 --> 00:19:31.720
Signal is a messenger for your phone contacts.

00:19:31.830 --> 00:19:36.290
Instead, our protocol is an invite-only layer, with

00:19:36.290 --> 00:19:38.960
a doorway that you can open to app proto as wide as

00:19:39.040 --> 00:19:39.670
you want.

00:19:40.360 --> 00:19:43.390
You're always in charge of who gets the keys to talk

00:19:43.390 --> 00:19:43.990
to you.

00:19:44.080 --> 00:19:48.220
Messaging has become crowded and spammy.

00:19:48.230 --> 00:19:52.880
We're empowering you to rebuild the network of who you actually

00:19:52.910 --> 00:19:56.220
want to talk to, with the identities that you already know

00:19:56.220 --> 00:19:56.830
them as.

00:19:56.860 --> 00:20:01.530
I want to close with a postscript for a solar punk

00:20:01.770 --> 00:20:02.950
future.

00:20:03.100 --> 00:20:08.860
Double Ratchet is known as the Axolotl algorithm

00:20:08.860 --> 00:20:12.120
, because it is cryptographically self-healing,

00:20:12.140 --> 00:20:14.980
the way the Mexico City salamander, the Ajol

00:20:14.980 --> 00:20:17.320
ote, from Nahuatl, Ajolotl,

00:20:17.320 --> 00:20:18.360
is self-healing.

00:20:18.480 --> 00:20:23.680
When LDF was Tetnotichlan, it was a

00:20:24.080 --> 00:20:28.550
sustainable city on a lake in a volcanic mountain basin, and

00:20:28.550 --> 00:20:30.950
Ajolotes were extremely plentiful.

00:20:32.500 --> 00:20:35.870
Now, there are more Ajolotes in captivity for medical

00:20:35.870 --> 00:20:38.180
research than living in the wild.

00:20:38.190 --> 00:20:42.680
The legend goes that when there are no more Ajolotes

00:20:42.680 --> 00:20:44.040
, the world will end.

00:20:44.050 --> 00:20:48.030
There are currently estimated to be between 50 and 1,000

00:20:48.030 --> 00:20:49.090
wild Ajolotes.

00:20:51.110 --> 00:20:54.510
There are entities that we are in relation to on this earth

00:20:54.540 --> 00:20:57.400
that can't express their consent with language.

00:20:57.420 --> 00:20:59.760
They only register their distress.

00:21:03.830 --> 00:21:06.350
Protocols scale how we relate to each other.

00:21:06.540 --> 00:21:10.490
The GERM protocol scales the granting and withdrawal of consent

00:21:10.490 --> 00:21:13.940
in relationships with humans and with robots.

00:21:14.940 --> 00:21:18.630
As we continue to rebuild the world through technology, let's

00:21:18.900 --> 00:21:22.130
never skip the hard work of negotiating consent in all of our

00:21:22.130 --> 00:21:23.290
relationships.

00:21:24.200 --> 00:21:27.090
Because even if people can leave our apps, if they don

00:21:27.090 --> 00:21:29.410
't like them, which we talk about a lot in At

00:21:29.410 --> 00:21:32.490
Proto, we want them to keep choosing At Proto

00:21:32.520 --> 00:21:32.840
.

00:21:32.850 --> 00:21:37.130
So let's use our interacting protocols to build a future that

00:21:37.130 --> 00:21:40.330
is truly free, because we are all exactly where we want

00:21:40.330 --> 00:21:40.750
to be.

00:21:40.880 --> 00:21:41.780
Thank you.

00:21:41.900 --> 00:21:51.070
And I did want to hold like

00:21:51.110 --> 00:21:59.180
a few minutes for Q&A,

00:21:59.180 --> 00:22:01.080
so if anybody has any, hit me up.

00:22:01.100 --> 00:22:01.890
Yeah, Gov.

00:22:02.010 --> 00:22:04.520
Hang on just a sec.

00:22:04.740 --> 00:22:06.630
We've got folks streaming in, so I'll bring you

00:22:06.630 --> 00:22:07.080
a mic.

00:22:07.220 --> 00:22:09.080
Thank you.

00:22:10.080 --> 00:22:12.380
So, well, thank you very much.

00:22:12.380 --> 00:22:13.810
And I also sent my first GERM DM, like

00:22:13.810 --> 00:22:14.740
, right now, so.

00:22:14.760 --> 00:22:17.710
As you all should, right now.

00:22:17.740 --> 00:22:18.440
As you all should.

00:22:18.450 --> 00:22:22.150
But, so with E2EE, and also in the

00:22:22.400 --> 00:22:27.870
context of consent, there's always a tension between privacy and

00:22:27.870 --> 00:22:30.400
safety, from a security perspective.

00:22:30.410 --> 00:22:32.500
And I'm curious what your approach, or GERM

00:22:32.540 --> 00:22:35.520
's approach, is towards that, perhaps in the context of

00:22:35.520 --> 00:22:36.400
moderation.

00:22:36.420 --> 00:22:38.600
Yeah, pretty much that's my question.

00:22:40.080 --> 00:22:42.460
At GERM, we have a user-centric view

00:22:42.460 --> 00:22:43.420
of safety.

00:22:43.430 --> 00:22:47.060
So it's all about people being empowered to be in places

00:22:47.380 --> 00:22:50.140
that they want to be, and consent is really central to

00:22:50.140 --> 00:22:50.540
that.

00:22:50.560 --> 00:22:53.950
And on a kind of organizational level, we have a sense

00:22:53.960 --> 00:22:57.780
that we're going to build and ship safety features along with

00:22:57.780 --> 00:23:00.490
the connective features that we ship.

00:23:01.020 --> 00:23:03.540
So the GERM that many of you are using today

00:23:03.630 --> 00:23:05.580
is a one-on-one messenger.

00:23:05.580 --> 00:23:08.990
We haven't shipped photos yet, also for safety reasons,

00:23:09.020 --> 00:23:11.120
because there's tooling that we need to ship once we let

00:23:11.280 --> 00:23:11.960
people share photos.

00:23:11.980 --> 00:23:14.120
There's tooling that we need to ship also when we let

00:23:14.120 --> 00:23:18.680
you share link previews, which we all want link preview

00:23:18.680 --> 00:23:18.970
s.

00:23:19.240 --> 00:23:20.960
I've been thinking about that a lot this weekend.

00:23:20.970 --> 00:23:23.990
It's also why we haven't shipped open DMs yet

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:24.300
.

00:23:24.300 --> 00:23:26.420
A lot of people have been asking for DMs.

00:23:26.420 --> 00:23:28.020
So we have a lot to build.

00:23:28.020 --> 00:23:30.340
We don't want to put the cart before the horse.

00:23:30.340 --> 00:23:33.900
We want to make sure that anywhere that people are, they

00:23:33.900 --> 00:23:37.260
are able to get help if they need it.

00:23:37.680 --> 00:23:41.090
We also think about scale when we think about safety.

00:23:41.230 --> 00:23:45.880
So we think that people have a right to community, but

00:23:45.880 --> 00:23:49.690
they don't have a right to reach and, like,

00:23:49.940 --> 00:23:50.770
extensive publishing.

00:23:50.890 --> 00:23:55.140
So when we envision GERM serving extra large groups,

00:23:55.140 --> 00:23:58.890
we imagine that perhaps, like, an automated moderation service that

00:23:58.890 --> 00:24:01.570
will be required to be an end in your group.

00:24:01.590 --> 00:24:04.720
But that's not something that will require in small-scale

00:24:04.720 --> 00:24:06.980
groups, like 20-person groups.

00:24:07.580 --> 00:24:10.450
And, you know, even though we're innovating a

00:24:10.450 --> 00:24:13.770
lot in terms of the protocol and the identity layer, we

00:24:13.770 --> 00:24:16.580
are building on top of 10, 15 years of end-

00:24:16.660 --> 00:24:18.310
to-end encrypted messaging.

00:24:18.540 --> 00:24:21.070
Billions of people are using end-to-end encrypted

00:24:21.130 --> 00:24:24.000
messaging every day around the world in iMessage and

00:24:24.220 --> 00:24:24.380
WhatsApp.

00:24:24.380 --> 00:24:26.530
And so there are a lot of best practices there for us

00:24:26.530 --> 00:24:27.010
to build on.

00:24:27.340 --> 00:24:28.390
Thanks.

00:24:28.560 --> 00:24:31.740
Here you go.

00:24:31.880 --> 00:24:34.080
Thank you.

00:24:34.500 --> 00:24:37.000
What are the requirements for implementing GERM DMs into

00:24:37.090 --> 00:24:37.890
your app view?

00:24:37.940 --> 00:24:40.440
We have them written up.

00:24:40.470 --> 00:24:43.120
There's links to them right on our blog, germnet

00:24:43.300 --> 00:24:43.680
work.

00:24:43.680 --> 00:24:44.840
com slash blog.

00:24:44.850 --> 00:24:46.010
You should ask Anna.

00:24:46.020 --> 00:24:46.860
Anna, can you raise your hand?

00:24:46.860 --> 00:24:47.420
Show the people.

00:24:47.460 --> 00:24:49.620
Ask Anna's my founding engineer.

00:24:49.640 --> 00:24:52.240
What are the requirements?

00:24:52.460 --> 00:24:54.890
Okay.

00:24:55.020 --> 00:24:55.700
It's complicated.

00:24:55.700 --> 00:24:58.440
I mean, from a user experience level today, we're

00:24:58.540 --> 00:24:59.320
just on iOS.

00:24:59.330 --> 00:25:01.990
So you're going to want to have an app or a

00:25:02.110 --> 00:25:05.560
web product that people are using, at least on their iPhone

00:25:05.560 --> 00:25:06.230
sometimes.

00:25:06.250 --> 00:25:08.870
And we have some splash pages and ways for you to direct

00:25:09.090 --> 00:25:12.220
folks to information if they're not using an iOS device when

00:25:12.220 --> 00:25:13.160
they access.

00:25:13.180 --> 00:25:14.470
But it should be pretty easy.

00:25:14.490 --> 00:25:16.080
Lots of people have done it, even in the last few

00:25:16.080 --> 00:25:17.110
weeks, without our help yet.

00:25:17.320 --> 00:25:18.510
So we'd love to help you do that.

00:25:18.560 --> 00:25:18.990
Great.

00:25:19.010 --> 00:25:22.160
And are there any pretenses on which you would prevent an

00:25:22.160 --> 00:25:24.770
app view from implementing GERM DMs, like if

00:25:24.770 --> 00:25:27.130
they became, you know, like an abuser of the

00:25:27.130 --> 00:25:29.230
technology or something like this?

00:25:29.300 --> 00:25:31.810
I think that would be difficult.

00:25:31.850 --> 00:25:35.250
That's an interesting trust and safety question.

00:25:35.360 --> 00:25:37.990
I think there are ways that we can...

00:25:38.060 --> 00:25:39.780
I'm not actually going to answer that.

00:25:39.780 --> 00:25:40.810
We should chat about that.

00:25:40.860 --> 00:25:41.100
Yeah.

00:25:41.100 --> 00:25:41.440
Thank you.

00:25:41.440 --> 00:25:42.160
I'll check out the docs.

00:25:42.210 --> 00:25:42.820
Thank you very much.

00:25:42.820 --> 00:25:43.040
Yeah, please do.

00:25:45.170 --> 00:25:46.410
Someone throw me an easy one.

00:25:46.550 --> 00:25:50.080
One more, maybe?

00:25:50.390 --> 00:25:52.220
What was your favorite part of building on Ad Proto?

00:25:52.240 --> 00:25:53.980
All of you.

00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:54.540
Excellent.

00:25:54.560 --> 00:25:56.790
No, but to say it, like, more actually,

00:25:56.790 --> 00:26:00.660
more directly, it's kind of ironic when you're building

00:26:00.740 --> 00:26:03.840
, like, a consumer product to build something that's designed

00:26:03.920 --> 00:26:05.780
to have a cold start problem on purpose.

00:26:06.040 --> 00:26:08.340
Because the whole point of GERM is that you can

00:26:08.340 --> 00:26:10.690
be alone if you want to, and you control the aperture

00:26:10.690 --> 00:26:12.920
of how available you want to be.

00:26:13.260 --> 00:26:15.660
So somebody might use GERM and only ever want to

00:26:15.660 --> 00:26:18.480
talk to three people in their entire lives, but one of

00:26:18.480 --> 00:26:21.030
the three people that they're talking to might want to talk

00:26:21.140 --> 00:26:22.540
to 50,000 people.

00:26:22.610 --> 00:26:25.620
And that's an affordance that we make possible that the

00:26:25.640 --> 00:26:28.680
meta products of the world make simply impossible.

00:26:28.700 --> 00:26:31.190
And I think the last six months for us, as we

00:26:31.190 --> 00:26:34.500
've integrated with Ad Proto, has been about giving you

00:26:34.500 --> 00:26:37.440
a new aperture and a new set of invitations that you

00:26:37.440 --> 00:26:39.900
can use to bring your friends into GERM.

00:26:40.090 --> 00:26:42.710
And just seeing those GERM buttons pop up all over

00:26:42.920 --> 00:26:47.000
your profiles and seeing people use this to have private conversations from

00:26:47.210 --> 00:26:50.620
their internet friends has been extremely thrilling.

00:26:50.620 --> 00:26:51.760
So thank you for that.

00:26:51.770 --> 00:26:53.400
Thank you so much, Tessa.

00:26:53.400 --> 00:26:55.240
I think we're going to wrap up questions now, and

00:26:55.240 --> 00:26:57.640
we've got a panel discussion, so everybody stick around.

00:26:57.650 --> 00:27:00.530
The team from Expo and Friends is going to be talking

00:27:00.530 --> 00:27:03.120
about building apps on Expo and at Proto.

00:27:03.230 --> 00:27:04.300
Thank you.

00:27:04.430 --> 00:27:05.280
Thank you so much, Tessa.

00:27:05.300 --> 00:27:06.310
Thank you.
